Solving
Quadratic
Inequalities
Why
You can solve many real-world
problems, such as those involving
business profits related to revenue and
cost, by solving quadratic inequalities.
Katie makes and sells T-shirts. A consultant found that her monthly costs, C,
are related to the selling price, p, of the shirts by the function C(p) = 75p + 2500.
The revenue, R, from the sale of the shirts is represented by R(p) = -25p² + 700p.
Her profit, P, is the difference between the revenue and the costs each month.
P(p) = R(p) - C(p)
= -25p² + 700p - (75p +2500)
= -25p² +625p - 2500
For what range of prices can Katie sell the shirts in order to make a profit?
That is, for what values of p will -25p² +625p -2500 > 0? You will answer this
question in Example 2.
